There are a few different ways you can create an admin user in Firebase, but one common approach is to add a custom claim to their user account. This custom claim will be used in Firebase security rules to grant elevated permissions to this user.

Here's an example of how to set up an admin user with custom claims using Firebase admin SDK:

1. Install the Firebase admin SDK in your server-side code.

```
npm install firebase-admin
```

2. Create a new Firebase admin SDK project if you haven't already. Go to the Firebase console and select your project, then click on the gear icon next to "Project Overview" and select "Project settings". Under the "Service Accounts" tab, click on "Generate new private key" to download a JSON file that contains your Firebase admin credentials.

3. In your server-side code, initialize the Firebase admin SDK with your service account credentials.

```javascript
const admin = require('firebase-admin');

const serviceAccount = require('./path/to/serviceAccountKey.json');

admin.initializeApp({
  credential: admin.credential.cert(serviceAccount),
  databaseURL: 'https://your-project-id.firebaseio.com'
});

const auth = admin.auth();
```

4. To create an admin user, use the admin SDK to update their user account with a custom claim.

```javascript
const uid = 'some-uid'; // the UID of the user you want to make an admin

// Set admin custom claim on user with the given UID.
auth.setCustomUserClaims(uid, { admin: true })
  .then(() => {
    console.log('Custom claim set for user:', uid);
    // The new custom claims will propagate to the user's ID token the
    // next time a new one is issued.
  })
  .catch((error) => {
    console.log('Error setting custom claim:', error);
  });
```

This will set a custom claim called "admin" on the user's account, indicating that they are an administrator.

5. In your Firebase security rules, use this custom claim to allow access to certain parts of your database.

```javascript
{
  "rules": {
    "some-node": {
      ".read": "auth.token.admin === true",
      ".write": "auth.token.admin === true"
    }
  }
}
```

This would allow users with the "admin" custom claim to read from and write to the "some-node" node in your database.

Note: You should make sure that you secure your server-side code that's allowed to set custom claims appropriately. You don't want just anyone to be able to add admin permissions to arbitrary users!

